<gtr:projectOverview xmlns:gtr="http://gtr.ukri.org/api"><gtr:projectComposition><gtr:collaborations/><gtr:leadResearchOrganisation url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/C6D0044A-2CD2-4167-B90B-922AF53E361F"><gtr:id>C6D0044A-2CD2-4167-B90B-922AF53E361F</gtr:id><gtr:name>University of Kent</gtr:name><gtr:department>Sch of Anthropology &amp; Conservation</gtr:department><gtr:address><gtr:line1>The Registry</gtr:line1><gtr:line4>Canterbury</gtr:line4><gtr:line5>Kent</gtr:line5><gtr:postCode>CT2 7NZ</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>South East</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:typeInd>RO</gtr:typeInd></gtr:leadResearchOrganisation><gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:organisationRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/C6D0044A-2CD2-4167-B90B-922AF53E361F"><gtr:id>C6D0044A-2CD2-4167-B90B-922AF53E361F</gtr:id><gtr:name>University of Kent</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>The Registry</gtr:line1><gtr:line4>Canterbury</gtr:line4><gtr:line5>Kent</gtr:line5><gtr:postCode>CT2 7NZ</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>South East</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>LEAD_RO</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole></gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/DF244727-F660-4BE1-95A3-CF6F5F83856C"><gtr:id>DF244727-F660-4BE1-95A3-CF6F5F83856C</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Julian</gtr:firstName><gtr:otherNames>Chee</gtr:otherNames><gtr:surname>Lee</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FF003234%2F1"><gtr:id>F4056DEB-19FD-432E-A282-57D81EA66DAD</gtr:id><gtr:title>Islamisation in Malaysia: Causes and Contexts</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/F003234/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>Although once considered a secular democracy, Malaysia has become increasingly 'Islamised' in recent years, and Muslim Malaysians often emphasise their religious identity over their national identity. This change is particularly apparent in politics, where demands are often made in terms of Islamic obligations. Also, the policing of morality according to orthodox Islamic sensibilities is gaining increasing state backing.
&lt;br />
&lt;br />This Islamisation has not gone unopposed, however: three groups - secularly oriented lawyers, progressive Muslim activists and opposition political party members - have been developing a network to resist this movement. These groups are particularly concerned about the way in which political Islam is forming the underlying political framework of Malaysia.
&lt;br />
&lt;br />This project seeks to draw out the relationship between Islam, political expediencies, and inter-ethnic relations in Malaysia in order to explain Malaysia's Islamisation. This project will also compare the development of political Islam in Malaysia to other countries in the region, in particular Indonesia.
&lt;br />
&lt;br />The data on which this project is predominantly founded was gathered through participant-observation and interviews that took place between 2004 and 2006, during the researcher's PhD candidature.
